@flexiarg peeragogy/reciprocal-participation
@title Give Back to the Communities You Extract From
@keywords reciprocal, give-back, social-contract, design-justice, indigenous-data, feminist-data, anti-extractive, ethics, data-coloniality, tierra-comun
@audience researchers, facilitators, project conveners, anyone collecting community knowledge or data
@tone practical
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/wrapper peeragogy/roles peeragogy/use-or-make collaboration-coherence/isolation collaboration-coherence/magical-thinking]

! conclusion: Any practice that collects knowledge, data, or stories from a community needs an explicit answer to "what does the community get back?" — articulated as a discipline, not left as an afterthought.  Reciprocal participation makes the give-back move a first-class part of the practice's design, drawing on indigenous data frameworks, feminist data frameworks, and Design Justice.  The discipline distinguishes peer-learning practice from extractive research, ethics-board-as-window-dressing, and well-meaning-but-asymmetric volunteer recruitment.
  + context: A peer-learning project draws on community participation — interviews, contributed material, lived-experience stories, identifiable data, co-authored work.  The project produces an output (a paper, a handbook, a podcast, a tool, a curriculum).  Without an explicit reciprocity discipline, the project's benefits accrue to the producers and the give-back is left implicit ("we'll share the result somewhere"), unmeasured, or absent.  Reciprocal participation is the move from implicit-and-discretionary to explicit-and-tracked.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: producing-the-output ↔ giving-back-to-sources.
    Real: producing the output and giving back to the sources are two different kinds of labor.  Without the discipline, output-production is the work that has deadlines and accountability, while give-back is what happens "if there's time."  That asymmetry compounds across years and across many projects, and the producing side accrues credentials, citations, and funding while the source side accrues nothing tracked.
    Irreducible: the people whose voices the practice carries cannot fully guard their own reciprocity if the practice itself doesn't make it a constraint.  The convener has more agency in the relationship than the contributor; the discipline puts that asymmetry on the table rather than papering over it with rhetoric.
    Active: the pull recurs every time the practice uses contributed material — every transcript quoted, every dataset analysed, every story retold, every workshop's emergent insight written up by one party.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Up-front contract: before extraction begins, the practice and the community agree on what will be returned (a copy of the artifact, a share of attention, a tangible service, a portion of any funding).  The agreement is documented and revisited as the project proceeds.
    (2) Built-in attribution: the practice's outputs name contributors specifically and link to whatever they want named — not as a courtesy at the end but as a structural element of the artifact, with versioning so attribution doesn't decay.
    (3) Translation-back: the practice translates its outputs back into forms the contributing community can use (a plain-language version, a community-language translation, a tool the community asked for, a workshop run for them).
    (4) Material reciprocity: when the practice receives funding, recognition, or career advancement based on contributed work, a defined share returns to the sources — financially, in resources, or in concrete labor.
    (5) Refusal-on-asymmetry: the practice declines to use contributed material when reciprocity isn't actually possible, instead of using it on the assumption that reciprocity will be worked out later.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: contributors can name what they get from the practice using their material, the practice can name what it gives back, and the two descriptions roughly match.  Failing when: contributors see the artifact for the first time alongside the general public, or the practice's give-back consists of "we put it on the website."
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Implicit reciprocity: the practice describes its give-back vaguely ("benefits the wider community") without naming what specifically goes where.
    - Attribution-as-acknowledgment: contributors are listed in an acknowledgments section but receive nothing material.
    - Window-dressing ethics: the practice has an ethics board or ethics statement but the affected communities are not represented in either.
    - Volunteer-funnel asymmetry: the practice consistently recruits volunteers who do real labor without commensurate return, while the producers' careers advance.
    - Asymmetric publishing: the practice publishes outputs in venues the contributing communities cannot access (paywalled journals, conferences they can't travel to) without producing accessible versions.

  + provenance: This pattern surfaced from the 2026-04-29 posterior-pass analysis of the Peeragogy Podcast (M-peeragogy-rewrite mission), specifically episode 5 ("The Ethics of Data") with Yasmin Bidyoff (Ada Lovelace Institute, no-tech-for-tyrants) and Paola Ricaurte (Tecnológico de Monterrey, Tierra Común Network, A+ Alliance).  Paola: *"if we extract something from the community, we should give back that as well."*  Yasmin: *"a reciprocal participation, social contract sort of thing."*  Both articulated the same move from different vantage points — data-extraction ethics in Paola's case (drawing on indigenous data frameworks, feminist data frameworks, and Design Justice); researcher-participant relationship in Yasmin's case.  The Handbook's chapter 17 (Peeragogical Assessment) hints at reciprocity through its "learning is adaptation" gloss but does not formalise reciprocal participation as a first-class discipline.
